Also, particularly in the sciences, there is a lack of diverse subject matters being offered, and some classes are incredibly hard to get into during the first 2 years due to a lack of open spots in those courses.

Q41: Dominican, like many small schools, isn't necessarily for everyone. The course variety is lacking, some professors are not great and you may be forced to take them because there's only one course that can fit your schedule, and you have to take seminars which are an absolute waste of 12 credits. I wish Dominican allowed you to use those 12 credits toward relevant courses, and increased the number and subject matter of courses they offer. Q80:
A close friend of mine, a junior in the Rosary College of Arts and Sciences (studying Chemistry), came to me for some advice. She is a very involved and academically gifted student. She was in the process of applying to a very prestigious research program at Northwestern University and needed help in the application process. She wanted to know how to make a resume and asked me “what it was in the first place”, “what should go on it”, “how to format it”, “where to send it”, etcetera. She also asked me “how to interview”, “what LinkedIn was”, and “how to conduct an informational interview.” She was obviously very overwhelmed and was unsure how to do anything career-related; in fact, she had only heard about the Northwestern program from one of her professors. After she asked all of these questions and expressed how overwhelmed she was - I thought to myself, this is unacceptable. It is shocking that she has had no prior career development requirements and had not worked on anything Career-related for any of current or past classes (nor will she for her future classes). This was/is a problem. 
The Problem:
There are numerous Majors at Dominican University that do not have any formal elements of Career Development worked into their curriculum. Simply put, undergraduate students, in general, do not complete something unless it is required of them. According to the National Survey of Student Engagement 2018 conducted at Dominican University, 75% of Dominican students work off-campus by their senior year. They do not have time to go to elective career events or enroll in non-degree seeking classes. Additionally, according to a presentation given by the Office of Institutional Effectiveness titled, Examining the Class of 2022, 92% of the Dominican University graduating class of 2022 responded that “being able to get a better job” was “very important” in their choice to attend college in the first place. All students should be equally prepared to enter the job market post their completion of an Undergraduate degree at Dominican University. 
Research Plan and Process
Prior to the COVID-19 pandemic, I had prepared an exhaustive qualtrics survey to send to the general student body. This qualtrics survey was designed to gauge where the general student body was in terms of the knowledge, use, and satisfaction of the Career Development office. In addition to the qualtrics survey, I had prepared a somewhat elaborate timeline. It has planned communications with senior staff members in respective departments, requests for data and information, etc. 
Obviously, due to the pandemic, I had to adjust my research plan. Instead of gathering the information I wanted myself, I utilized several surveys conducted by the Office of Institutional Effectiveness. The data they had that was relevant to my project is from 2018. However, it is worth noting that it will still reflect general trends in the need for and satisfaction of Career Development. The information that I originally would’ve collected from my qualtrics survey would’ve informed how much change would be needed in terms of Career Development. I also would’ve liked to examine the data by individual categories - what Career Development needed the most work (or lacked the most understanding), which majors lacked the most understanding, various schools, commuter vs residents, demographics, etc. Each individual category of the questions asked in my qualtrics survey would have indicated which area in career development needed to be addressed. 
More relevant to this paper - Currently, I have adjusted my research plan, timeline, and proposal significantly. I was able to speak with  Keli Wojciechowski on April 6th. We spoke regarding the details of the survey. Keli spoke with Dr. Barrington Price who deemed sending out the survey unnecessary due to the possibility of a negative student bias during these trying quarantined times. I also spoke with Norah Collins-Pienta regarding my plan, adjusting to COVID, and how this will affect my proposal. 
Community Perceptions 
Based on several surveys conducted by the Office of Institutional Effectiveness (National Survey of Student Engagement 2018 results, Graduating Student Survey Summary Findings, Examining the Class of 2022, Entering Student Profile and Enrollment Trend Analysis) Dominican students, in general, would not be opposed to an increase in focus to career development. This is where I wanted to gauge the reaction from the general community in my personal survey. This is a step that would need to be taken, obviously, before an actions steps were taken.
I conducted a little under 20 student interviews in early February. I asked the students how they felt about career development, if they thought Dominican was offering enough support in that aspect, and if they would be opposed to learning more about career development. From the thirty students I interviewed, I determined I needed to create and distribute a much more comprehensive survey to determine how students felt and what was needed. Although this is no longer possible, I am confident that students would be more successful post-undergraduate if they had a more comprehensive career development background. Regardless, almost every student I interviewed felt unprepared (except for those students in the Brennan School of Business).
Proposed Solution
Incorporating a mandatory annual visit to Career Development into the Seminar series. This would be monitored by seminar professors (freshmen through senior). There are some things that would need to happen before moving forward with anything like this. A community survey (the qualtrics survey I created, or something like it) would need to be distributed. As stated above in previous sections, the need for Career Development to become more prevalent in our curriculum is obvious. However, the question is to what extent it needs to be addressed. I believe the bold step of adding 
Obviously, this would have to have approval from Sheila Bauer-Gatsos/approval from the faculty senate. However, I believe this proposal would do the most good, at the least cost. Students would have to forego 1 session’s worth of content to cover career-related items. Surely that would not completely require an entire remake of the seminar model. Some other proposed ideas or honorable mentions included requiring all students to enroll in the current Career Development 1 credit course (ID 110) their first semester at Dominican or incorporating Career Development’s four-year plan into some sort of mandatory check-in system (ensuring all students meet with Career Development annually).
Identification & Development of Proposed Solution
The data collected from the various campus-wide surveys completed by the office of institutional Effectiveness, towards a need in career development. The data shows that there is a  strong positive trend in new College applicants applying to / attending universities with the sole focus of getting better job opportunities. Despite this, Dominican University has not focused as much on Career Development as their students would want them to, at least proportionally. There is a somewhat high satisfaction rate with the current career development structure; however, just because there is already satisfaction amongst the student body does not mean there can not be an improvement. 
I am a senior enrolled in the 2017-2018 Brennan School of Business bulletin. This may not seem significant; however, it was crucial to me in the realization of a problem and eventually identification of a solution. By being part of the 2017-2018 Brennan bulletin (the “new business curriculum”), I am required to complete: at least 40 hours of an internship (pre-approved by the Director of the Brennan Career Development Program), plus 4 credit hours of required Career Development courses; known as BCDP or Brennan Career Development Program. By examining and comparing the 2014 and 2017 Brennan Bulletins, it is obvious that the 2014 curriculum was completely lacking in Career Development. This is the one reason why almost all Dominican students chose to attend college in the first place, yet there were no requirements or focus on the topic. Brennan identified and swiftly addressed this problem. Due to being a student in the 2017 bulletin, I certainly feel like I am fully qualified to enter my field of work post-undergrad. I have completed the four required career development courses and have real-life experience via my internship. I am privy to this knowledge/experience only because of the drastic change in curriculum. This is not the case for Brennan students prior to 2017 and almost all other Dominican Students. I believe a similar model can be applied campus-wide. 
As mentioned above in the honorable mentions, I have adjusted this plan several times. Due to both COVID19 and data leading me in a different direction. I originally thought that each major should have an individualized course created for that major, regarding career opportunities and alternative routes. Although this might be ideal, it would be a very large ask. coordinating a campus-wide effort to increase career development in the classroom, is a large ask in and of itself. However, when scaling this into the creation of various new classes, it becomes even more difficult. Therefore the next best thing to creating a new class is adding something to an existing class. 
Cost-Benefit Analysis 
There are several benefits for students in this proposal. Students would essentially be better equipped to enter the job market without having to do much extra work; as it would only be added to seminar, rather than an additional class. They would have the most relevant information about their career development. This would also increase the number of students who have jobs post completion of their undergraduate degree. Our students would also have more to contribute to their current or future classes after having gained the appropriate career knowledge; especially in their major-specific classes. Dominican would be perceived as a results-driven university; a nice complement to our Caritas et Veritas. 
However, there are also some opportunity costs associated with this proposed solution. Students would be losing the content taught in the singular session they would have to go to the Career Development office (rather Keli or Maria lecturing in the class). In addition to the faculty members that may need to adjust their syllabi to accommodate this addition. I’m also sure the faculty members would not be appreciative of changes being made in the general curriculum. I would imagine that the student would not be opposed to this; however, I would want the qualtrics survey results to make an informed decision. You would need to add a proposed solutions section, giving students the option to choose what they think would be best. One limitation would be if students simply did not complete the required career assignments (writing a resume, completing a virtual interview, etc.) or attend the required session. 
Recommendation 
To continue this project, several steps would need to be taken to ensure my proposed solution is appropriate (assuming it is feasible). Firstly, the qualtrics survey would need to be sent out. This would ensure we receive quality data on what is needed in terms of Dominican University’s Career Development. Also, it would indicate what students felt would be appropriate In correcting whatever problem is found in the survey. After conducting the survey, the proposal would need to be reevaluated to judge whether or not it is still correct. Further research should also include which aspects of the Career Development 4 year plan and ID 110 should be incorporated into the seminar program; obviously, this should be done prior to bringing this to Sheila. Someone should also gauge reaction from the faculty senate; as I assume unfortunately this proposal would be somewhat controversial (regarding the politics of general curriculum approval). 
My overall recommendation would be to make some improvements to the current Career Development program; rather what is taught about the subject in general. There is a clear lack of knowledge based on my initial interviews, the qualtrics survey should confirm my hypothesis. I would recommend adding Career Development related content by adding a class, adding to a current set of classes, requiring ID 210, or requiring visits to the Career Development office.

Require courses on taxes, and financial literacy instead of seminars that teach people nothing. But I must say it is possible to reform the courses to be less pandering to the students direction and more blunt and confrontational, even argumentative  as that would lay peoples bare unfiltered biases on the table and lead to true inspection that can be shaped. Q87: Really the biggest problem with all the student services at Dominican is lack of communication and respect towards its students. The school kind of seems like everyone's running around with their heads cut off and nobody really knows what's going on. Students are referred to like eight different people when asking questions, until we are left to fix the problem ourselves - even if it makes us look like we're causing a disruption. If the goal was to prepare us for a world that is full of frustration and lack of authentic understanding/sympathy, maybe don't put a 40k price tag on it (bit of an exaggeration, but I honestly don't think it's too far from the truth). It really feels like Dominican doesn't care about its students after Freshman year and it has a lack of respect towards students and other people working in different departments. If Dominican didn't preach all this stuff about "being there for the students - we're not like other schools!" then these problems would just be a shoulder shrug and a phrase similar to "it is what it is..." but the hypocrisy is probably the biggest problem. It looks bad to say that you're not like other schools, but then turn around and use "Other schools do it, so what's the problem?" as an excuse. The administration creates a negative, demeaning environment that victimizes students whenever they bring up any issue they have with the school. Dominican reminds me of the parent that does the bare minimum and then gets frustrated when students complain it isn't enough. The University is by no means a "bad" school. The professors are great for the most part, the education is solid, and I really feel like I have improved as a person inside and outside the classroom; however, Dominican is a community college disguised as a four-year private institution. This may seem like venting after a stressful last two and a half years, but these problems existed before the pandemic. How can the wellness center have empty cabinets when students need something as simple as Benadryl? How can the housing department project such casual threats against students, such as removal from campus, when a lot of the time they are devoid in meaning and only meant to cause the students to sweat? How can financial aid claim they are serving Hispanic communities, when there is very little support when latino/a students run into a snag with the system or money itself? How can anybody at the school justify the endless fines, ridiculous fees (like how many more dollars are you trying to squeeze out of me with unreal graduation fees and still have the audacity to have limited tickets for family members to attend it?), and just brain-smoothing, beating around the bush excuses for why the school must do all of these things. At the end of the day, I would rather the administration be straight up (even if they're not so nice), than present themselves as God-serving angels - when a lot of them really only care about their own agenda. For a school that constantly complains about politics, it's crazy how many people working here could be great politicians with the way the University has trained them - to talk a lot without saying much. In conclusion, this is why I am somewhat dissatisfied with the services at Dominican and I think if you put out a survey, you would see that most people regret coming here. The only justifying reason why I stayed was because the students and professors are some of the best people around who truly care. As it is with most of the world, the people at the top hold all the cards and play it to their advantage, not caring or understanding how much of an effect it has on the rest of us.

Q20: Due to Covid I was not able to attend all of my clinical rotations in person nor the simulation lab. My clinical rotation for my critical care class, which was supposed to be in the ICU, turned out to be on an oncology floor. While I am grateful for any experience working directly with patients, the patient population on this floor did not have much to do with what I was learning in my critical care didactic course. My clinical rotation for community health was home hospice, and had me commuting an average of about 250+ miles a week. I live in Wrigleyville in the city and I was driving out to Romeoville, sometimes only for about 4 clinical hours. In my final capstone clinical rotation, we were initially given the choice to have a rotation in either OB, MedSurg, or Pediatrics, but I was then placed without any explanation into a home health rotation. I was required to get 144 hours in 8 weeks, which was almost impossible seeing as my nurses caseload was constantly changing and often did not even give me 12 hours a week. Not to mention there were various patients who requested not to have a student in the home if it was not necessary. When I reached out to faculty regarding my concerns, I was told to contact the home health company myself and figure something out. Turned out the company did not have another nurse for me to shadow, so I had to get "Clinical" hours working in the Apple Home Health Care office downtown Chicago. I was not doing any type of direct patient care during these office days. Also, since the case load of my precepting nurse was so low, I had to attend clinical almost every day, except class days, even if we only had one patient to see. It was really frustrating and stressful because I was doing everything I could, but did not feel like I was getting as much support as I would have liked from the faculty on how to remedy this problem. I do want to point out that my nurse preceptor for this clinical rotation was excellent, and tried to give me as many hours as possible. It was just a little frustrating that I was scrambling to get clinical hours done working in an office while other students were getting hands on experience.

Q87: I'm not sure if it's because I was a transfer student, but I constantly felt like I had to be more proactive than other students tin order to not fall through the cracks.  For example, my counselor never explained CBL to me, couldn't recommend classes, and couldn't even answer basic questions about graduation requirements.  I had to asks a dozen disparate people, reconcile wildly different answers, and PRAY that even though no single person seemed to fully understand what I needed to do to graduate, that I would still be able to.  In the three semesters I was here, I felt completely adrift.  Even now, I half expect something to come up and prevent me from getting this degree in a couple days.
Q18: I understand that this is a Catholic University, however I was still bothered by the sheer amount I had to write about Christianity in my three semesters.  I did not take a single class about Christianity, but it was heavily prevalent in seminars and theology classes, even if the classes were not about Christianity.  As a Jewish person, it makes me feel duped to specifically sign up for one of the not overtly Christian seminars or theology classes and still find it to be the core framework of the class.  Meanwhile, I don't think I even heard someone obliquely reference Judaism, much less try to teach anything about it in our supremely anti-Semitic and hostile country.  In 2021, there was a record-breaking 34% rise in the number of hate crimes on Jewish people to over 2,700 incidents.  I don't know what a good solution would be here, but one thing that would help in the short term would be to please make it clear in course descriptions so that people can have informed consent over their next semester.
Q20: I mentioned this before, but I had to do CBL all on my own.  I tried to work with the office and connect with the ACLU over the summer and when that didn't work out, I got ghosted and forgotten about and told that I should just work at a food pantry.  Well, it's a good thing I checked with my professor because that would have been unacceptable and I would have had to do CBL all over again the following semester.  The problem is that this is my last semester.  If I'd had to stick around because of that mishandling of my CBL, I would have been furious.  It was bad enough spending the first 4 weeks of the semester getting it figured out.  This experience really made me feel like 1) I wasn't important to the school, 2) CBL wasn't important to the school, and 3) the psych manual that listed grad requirements, couldn't be trusted 100%.
Q41: Especially transfer students, I would not recommend.  In fact, I had multiple people explicitly warn me not to transfer to Dominican as it had a reputation for basically exactly what I've been describing this whole survey.
